{"title_page": "Lewis MacAdams", "text_new": "{{short description|American writer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Lewis MacAdams\n| image              = Lewis MacAdams.jpg\n| birth_date         = October 12, 1944\n| birth_place        = [[San Angelo, Texas]], U.S.\n| death_date         = April 21, 2020 (aged 75)\n| death_place        = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[Princeton University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[University at Buffalo]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n| known_for          = Co-founder of [[Friends of the Los Angeles River|FoLAR]]\n}}\n\n'''Lewis MacAdams''' (October 12, 1944 \u2013 April 21, 2020) was an American [[poet]], [[journalist]], [[political activist]], and [[filmmaker]].<ref name=\"auto\">[http://poetryandpoliticsanautobiography.blogspot.com Poetry and Politics-An Autobiography] \nby Lewis MacAdams</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMacAdams was born in [[San Angelo, Texas]] and grew up in [[Dallas]], where he graduated from [[St. Mark's School of Texas]] in 1962.<ref name=\"auto\" /> He then graduated from [[Princeton University]] in 1966.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1967/06/07/issue.html|title=TimesMachine: Wednesday June 7, 1967 - NYTimes.com|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com}}</ref> He then earned a Master's degree from the [[University at Buffalo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://legacy.lib.utexas.edu/taro/smu/00228/smu-00228.html|title=Lewis MacAdams papers A Guide|last=MacAdams|first=Lewis|website=legacy.lib.utexas.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nMacAdams was the author of a dozen books and tapes of poetry, and his poems have appeared in many anthologies. In 2001, he published his ''Birth of The Cool'', a cultural history of the idea of cool. As a journalist, MacAdams was a contributing editor of ''[[L.A. Weekly]]'' and wrote regularly on culture and ecology for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', ''[[Men\u2019s Journal]]'', the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', and ''Los Angeles'' magazine.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bigbridge.org/issue9/bios.htm#MacAdams|title=Big Bridge #9|website=www.bigbridge.org}}</ref> MacAdams was the director of the Poetry Center at [[San Francisco State University]] from 1975 to 1978.\n\nAs a political activist, MacAdams was a cofounder of [[Friends of the Los Angeles River]] (FoLAR) established in 1985 (and served as chair on their board of directors). FoLAR was characterized by MacAdams as a \"40 year art work\" to bring the Los Angeles River back to life. In the years which followed, he became the river\u2019s most important and influential advocate. Among FoLAR\u2019s many projects are an annual river clean-up, the \"Gran Limpieza,\" which brings 2500 people down to the river every spring to clean up; and an ongoing series of conferences and planning workshops dealing with every aspect of the river. Two of its current major goals are to create a Los Angeles River Conservancy to oversee restoration of the river, and a River Watch program to improve the River\u2019s water quality and target polluters<ref>.[http://www.folar.org Friends of the Los Angeles River] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716030537/https://folar.org/ |date=2019-07-16 }}</ref> \n \nIn 1991, MacAdams received the [[San Fernando Valley]] [[Audubon Society]]\u2019s annual Conservation Award.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> MacAdams' work, ''The River: Books One, Two & Three'', takes the Los Angeles River as its metaphor, weaving the story and song of the poet, activist and journalist as these three roles form the confluence which is the man.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.poetryflash.org/WS06.Press_Kit.html |title=Watershed 2006 |work=poetryflash.org|access-date=2009-12-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828190659/http://poetryflash.org/WS06.Press_Kit.html |archive-date=2008-08-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nOn April 21, 2020, MacAdams died at the age of 75 from complications of [[Parkinson\u2019s disease]]. He is survived by his three sons and his daughter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.losfelizledger.com/l-a-river-conservationist-lewis-macadams-dies-at-75/|title=L.A. River Conservationist Lewis MacAdams Dies at 75|last=Ledger|first=Los Feliz|date=2020-04-21|website=Los Feliz Ledger|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n\n===Books===\n*''City Money: Poems''. Burning Water (1966)  \n*''City Room''\n*''The Poetry Room''. New York: Harper & Row; First Edition (January 1, 1970) \n*''A Bolinas Report''\n*''Tilth''\n*''Dance'', pamphlet. Canton: The Institute of Further Studies; first edition (January 1, 1972)\n*''News From Niman Farm'', Tombouctou Books, 1976; first edition (November 1976)\n*''Live At The Church''. Kulchur Foundation (1977)\n*''Blind Date'', pamphlet. Am Here Books/Immediate Editions; first edition (January 1, 1981)\n*''The Angel'' (with Rita Degli Esposti & Gianantonio Pozzi)\n*''Africa and The Marriage of Walt Whitman and Marilyn Monroe''. Little Caesar Press (1982) \n*''The River, Books One & Two''. Palo Alto, CA: Blue Press, 1998\n*''Birth of the Cool: Beat, Bebop, and the American Avant-Garde''. New York: The Free Press, 2001\n*''The Family Trees'', (illustrated by Kim Abeles). Palo Alto, CA: Blue Press, 2001\n*''A Poem for the Dawn of the Terror Years''. Palo Alto, CA: Blue Press, 2003\n*''The River: Books One, Two, and Three''. Palo Alto, CA: Blue Press, revised second edition, 2007 \n*''Lyrics''. Palo Alto, CA: Blue Press, 2009\n*''Dear Oxygen''. New Orleans, LA: University of New Orleans Press, 2011\n\n===Audiotapes===\n*''To The Russian Women''\n*''And Now The News''\n*''Dear Oxygen'' (2007)\n\n===Articles===\n* \u201cPoetry and Politics.\u201d Talking poetics from Naropa Institute : annals of the Jack Kerouac School of Disembodied Poetics V. 2. Ed. Anne Waldman and Marilyn Webb, Boulder, Colo. : Shambhala, 1979\n* ''Remembering Jim Carroll''. Los Angeles Times. 16 September 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2009-sep-16-et-carroll16-story.html|title=A man of words, and the street|date=September 16, 2009|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n* {{cite journal| url=http://www.theparisreview.org/interviews/4241/the-art-of-poetry-no-10-robert-creeley| title=Robert Creeley, The Art of Poetry No. 10| work=The Paris Review| author=Lewis MacAdams and Linda Wagner-Martin| date=Fall 1968 }}\n\n==Films==\n*Hedirected (with Richard Lerner), ''What Happened to Kerouac?'' (1986)\n\n*Directed (with [[Jo Bonney]]), ''Funhouse'' (1986)  [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0295970/reference Funhouse (1986) - IMDb]\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of poets from the United States]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://oralhistory.library.ucla.edu/viewItem.do?ark=21198/zz00096kp9&title=MacAdams,%20Lewis Interview of Lewis MacAdams], part of [http://oralhistory.library.ucla.edu/viewItem.do?ark=21198/zz00094bm0&title=%20Environmental%20Activism%20in%20Los%20Angeles Environmental Activism in Los Angeles]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} interview series, Center for Oral History Research, UCLA Library Special Collections, University of California, Los Angeles.\n*[http://jacketmagazine.com/11/whalen-by-mac.html Q: What do I love about Philip Whalen's poems?] written for the L.A. Weekly on the occasion of the publication of [[Philip Whalen]]\u2019s Overtime, March, 1999 \n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090414080021/http://pdr.autono.net/cooledit.html Interview with Lewis MacAdams] subtitled: Birth of the Cool. Beat, Bebop and the American Avant-Garde. MacAdams is interviewed by Paul DeRienzo\n*[http://www.bigbridge.org/issue9/poetlmacadams.htm Grand Central Station] a chapbook of poems by MacAdams featured at Big Bridge#9\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20190716030537/https://folar.org/ Friends of the Los Angeles River] main website\n*[http://jacketmagazine.com/07/smit-r-mac.html Dale Smith reviews Lewis MacAdams]\n*[https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-ca-orhan-pamuk22-2009nov22,0,4473835.story Orhan Pamuk's L.A. stroll conjures up familiar sights] MacAdams article, which first appeared November 2009 in the [[L.A. Times]], discusses the Nobel prize-winning author [[Orhan Pamuk]], and his bond with Los Angeles' old-fashioned urban scape.\n*[http://www.kcet.org/socal/departures/lariver/downtown/lewis-macadams.html KCET Departures interview with Lewis Macadams] artist and advocate of the L.A. River\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macadams, Lewis}}\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:American literary critics]]\n[[Category:Writers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Writers from Texas]]\n[[Category:People from San Angelo, Texas]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles River]]\n[[Category:St. Mark's School (Texas) alumni]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths from Parkinson's disease]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American writer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Lewis MacAdams\n| image              = Lewis MacAdams.jpg\n| birth_date         = October 12, 1944\n| birth_place        = [[San Angelo, Texas]], U.S.\n| death_date         = April 21, 2020 (aged 75)\n| death_place        = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[Princeton University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[University at Buffalo]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n| known_for          = Co-founder of [[Friends of the Los Angeles River|FoLAR]]\n}}\n\n'''Lewis MacAdams''' (October 12, 1944 \u2013 April 21, 2020) was an American [[poet]], [[journalist]], [[political activist]], and [[filmmaker]].<ref name=\"auto\">[http://poetryandpoliticsanautobiography.blogspot.com Poetry and Politics-An Autobiography] \nby Lewis MacAdams</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMacAdams was born in [[San Angelo, Texas]] and